  "tax-calc-guide": {
    "titleEn": "Tax calculator - a guide to calculating taxes",
    "descriptionEn": "How to calculate personal income tax, tax deductions and refunds. A detailed guide to the tax calculator.",
    "contentEn": "## How to calculate taxes\n\nThe tax calculator helps you determine the tax amount, calculate deductions and plan your tax burden.\n\n## Main types of personal income tax\n\n| Rate | Application |\n|--------|----------|\n| 13% | Basic income (up to 5 million ₽/year) |\n| 15% | Income over 5 million ₽/year |\n| 30% | Income of non-residents |\n| 35% | Winnings, material benefits |\n\n## Tax deductions\n\n### Standard\n\n- For the first and second child - 1,400 ₽/month\n- For the third and subsequent ones - 3,000 ₽/month\n- Valid up to an income of 350,000 ₽ from the beginning of the year\n\n### Social\n\n- Training (your own or your children’s) - up to 120,000 ₽/year\n- Treatment - up to 120,000 ₽/year (expensive - without restrictions)\n- Charity - up to 25% of annual income\n\n### Property\n\n- Purchase of housing - up to 2,000,000 ₽ (return up to 260,000 ₽)\n- Mortgage interest - up to 3,000,000 ₽ (return up to 390,000 ₽)\n\n## How to get a deduction\n\nSubmit the 3-NDFL declaration through the taxpayer’s personal account or through your employer with an application and supporting documents.\n\nSee also: [Salary calculator](/tools/salary-calc), [Mortgage calculator](/tools/mortgage-calc)"
  },
  "tax-calc-tips": {
    "titleEn": "How to reduce taxes legally - 5 ways",
    "descriptionEn": "Legal ways to reduce the tax burden. Deductions, benefits and tax optimization strategies.",
    "contentEn": "## Legal ways to reduce taxes\n\n### 1. Complete all required deductions\n\nMany people forget about deductions for treatment, education and sports. Save receipts and contracts - the amount of the refund can be significant over the course of a year.\n\n### 2. Use IIS\n\nAn individual investment account gives the right to deduct:\n- Type A: refund of 13% of the contribution amount (up to 52,000 ₽/year)\n- Type B: income tax exemption\n\n### 3. Deduction for children\n\nDon't forget to file standard deductions for children through your employer. This is a small but stable saving every month.\n\n### 4. Long-term ownership of securities\n\nIf you own shares for more than 3 years, you can receive a deduction of up to RUB 3,000,000 for each year of ownership.\n\n### 5. Professional deductions for individual entrepreneurs\n\nIndividual entrepreneurs on OSNO can reduce the tax base by the amount of confirmed expenses.\n\n## Important to remember\n\n| Deadline | Action |\n|-----------|----------|\n| Until April 30 | Filing a 3-NDFL declaration |\n| Until July 15 | Payment of tax according to the declaration |\n| 3 years | Statute of limitations for tax refunds |\n\nDon't delay filing your deductions—you can get your taxes back for the last three years.\n\nSee also: [Salary calculator](/tools/salary-calc), [Interest calculator](/tools/percentage-calc)"
  },
  "tax-calc-use-cases": {
    "titleEn": "Tax calculation - practical examples",
    "descriptionEn": "Examples of calculating personal income tax, deductions and returns for different life situations.",
    "contentEn": "## Tax calculation examples\n\n### Example 1: Salary with a deduction for children\n\n- Salary: 80,000 ₽/month\n- Two children (deduction 1400 × 2 = 2800 ₽)\n- Tax base: 80,000 - 2,800 = 77,200 ₽\n- Personal income tax: 77,200 × 13% = 10,036 ₽\n- In hand: 69,964 ₽\n\nWithout the deduction, it would be 69,600 rubles. Savings: 364 ₽/month, 4,368 ₽/year.\n\n### Example 2: Refund for treatment\n\n- Treatment expenses: 95,000 ₽\n- Refund: 95,000 × 13% = 12,350 ₽\n\n### Example 3: Buying an apartment with a mortgage\n\n| Deduction | Base | Return |\n|-------|------|---------|\n| For purchase | 2,000,000 ₽ | 260,000 ₽ |\n| For interest | 1,500,000 ₽ (paid) | 195,000 ₽ |\n| Total | — | 455,000 ₽ |\n\n### Example 4: Income over 5 million\n\n- Annual income: 7,000,000 ₽\n- First 5,000,000 × 13% = 650,000 ₽\n- Remaining 2,000,000 × 15% = 300,000 ₽\n- Total personal income tax: 950,000 ₽\n\n## When to submit a declaration\n\nThe declaration is required when selling property, receiving rental income, winnings and income from sources abroad.\n\nSee also: [Salary calculator](/tools/salary-calc), [Mortgage calculator](/tools/mortgage-calc)"
  },
  "tip-calc-guide": {
    "titleEn": "Tip calculator - how to calculate tips correctly",
    "descriptionEn": "Guide to calculating tips. How much to leave in a restaurant, cafe and for other services.",
    "contentEn": "## How to calculate a tip\n\nThe tip calculator will help you quickly determine the tip amount and split the bill between participants.\n\n## Standard tip sizes\n\n| Service level | Tip size |\n|---------------------|--------------|\n| Excellent | 15-20% |\n| good | 10-15% |\n| Average | 5-10% |\n\n## Tipping by industry\n\n### Restaurants and cafes\n\nStandard - 10-15% of the invoice amount before discounts. If service is included in the bill (service fee), additional gratuity is at your discretion.\n\n### Food delivery\n\nCouriers are usually given 5-10% of the order or a fixed amount of 100-200 rubles.\n\n### Taxi\n\nTipping is optional, but 5-10% of the cost of the trip is considered good form, especially if the driver helped with luggage.\n\n### Hotels\n\n- Maid: 200-500 ₽/day\n- Receptionist: 100-200 ₽ per luggage\n- Concierge: depending on the situation\n\n## Dividing the account\n\nThe calculator will automatically divide the total amount (bill + tip) equally between the specified number of guests.\n\n## Rounding\n\nIt’s convenient to round the total amount to a round number—it makes paying easier for both you and your staff.\n\nSee also: [Interest Calculator](/tools/percentage-calc), [Discount Calculator](/tools/discount-calc)"
  },
  "tip-calc-tips": {
    "titleEn": "Tipping Etiquette - 5 Rules You Should Know",
    "descriptionEn": "Tipping rules in Russia and abroad. When and how much to leave, and when it is not accepted.",
    "contentEn": "## Tipping etiquette rules\n\n### 1. Tipping is a thank you, not an obligation.\n\nTipping is not mandatory in Russia, but it is a good way to express gratitude for quality service.\n\n### 2. Count tips from amount to discount\n\nIf you were given a discount or a promotional code was used, it is more correct to count the tip from the full cost - after all, the waiter worked the same way.\n\n### 3. Cash is preferred\n\nIf possible, leave tips in cash - this way they are guaranteed to go to a specific employee.\n\n### 4. Tipping abroad\n\n| Country | Size | Features |\n|--------|--------|------------|\n| USA | 18-25% | Mandatory, part of salary |\n| Europe | 5-10% | Often included in bill |\n| Japan | 0% | Not accepted, may offend |\n| Türkiye | 10-15% | Expected in restaurants |\n\n### 5. When tipping is not appropriate\n\n- In self-service establishments\n- If the service was unacceptable\n- In government agencies (may be regarded as a bribe)\n\n## Travel tip\n\nBefore traveling abroad, research local tipping traditions - they vary greatly from country to country.\n\nSee also: [Interest Calculator](/tools/percentage-calc), [Discount Calculator](/tools/discount-calc)"
  },
